column168: On August 2, 2016 at 0800 ET, Terminal personnel accidentally punctured a (1) 5-gallon metal containing UN1263 Paint Thinner "R7K54" during a forklift accident. On August 02, 2016 at 0600 ET, terminal personnel accidentally forked a (1) 55-gallon steel drum containing UN1104 Amyl acetates "Primary Amyl acetate Mixed Isomers" during a forklift accident. Approximately 8-gallons released to the trailer floor, the underlying concrete parking lot, and a catch basin. A contractor was dispatched who contained and cleaned the release. Boom were placed in the drain to collect the residual release. Absorbents ere applied and thoroughly worked into the impacted surfaces. (2) 55-gallon steel drums were generated containing impacted absorbents and labeled as haz-waste D001 due to the flash-point of 100 F which is also staged onsite for the terminal personnel to manage. They also generated (1) 85-gallon salvaged steel drum over-pack containing the damaged (1) 55-gallon steel drum which was staged onsite for the terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On 3 August 2016 at 1635, personnel on CSX train Q68902 parked at milepost ANJ814 discovered GATX212875, a loaded tank car of Waste Flammable Liquids, N.O.S. (Toluene, Xylene) carrying hazwaste manifest no. 004241342FLE, leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and Troup County Fire and GA DEP were notified. (CHEMTREC Report #2016-08-03-00273). HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a leak from the base of the liquid line valve. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Geocycle-AR George Colvin, 662-549-2860. Contractor personnel removed the valve and placed a cap/plug and decontaminated the car treated the ballast impacted by the spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move. 7.1 required? yes     Cause Code: 282. Threaded valve was tool-tight but just barely. Could have been much tighter. There were several exposed threads and very little thread sealant. It did not take much effort to loosen and remove the valve from the flange.   NARRI: 90

column168: PACKAGE WAS PUT ON TO ROLLERS GOING INTO A TRAILER TO BE LOADED. PACKAGE TIPPED OVER AND LEAKED DUE TO A LOOSE CAP ON A BOTTLE IN THE PACKAGE. LUKE GRUBER (LOADER) BRUSHED UP AGAINST THE PACKAGE AND GOT A SMALL AMOUNT ON HIS UPPER ARM. LUKE WENT TO THE NEAREST SINK AND RINSED HIS ARM AND THEN WASHED WITH SOAP AND WATER. I WAS CALLED TO THE TRAILER TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND EXAMINE LUKE. HIS UPPER ARM LOOKED VERY SLIGHTLY RED SO I ADVISED HIM TO RINSE HIS ARM FOR A FEW MORE MINUTES AS THE MSDS ADVISED TO FLUSH EXPOSED SKIN FOR SEVERAL MINUTES JUST TO BE SURE. AFTERWARDS HE SEEMED FINE AND DID NOT MENTION ANY PAIN NOR DID HIS SKIN SEEM TO BE REACTING ANY FURTHER THAN THE SLIGHT REDNESS OBSERVED BEFORE. I PUT SOME SODIUM BICARBONATE ON A SMALL AMOUNT THAT SPILLED ON THE FLOOR AS THE LIQUID TESTED AT ABOUT A 2 OR 3 WITH THE PH TAPE. I THEN BROUGHT THE PACKAGE AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO THE DMP CAGE FOR PROCESSING.
column169: SHIPPER ENSURE THAT THE CAPS ON THE PACKAGE ARE SEALED TIGHT. HAZMAT PACKAGES NOT PUT ON ROLLERS WHEN BEING LOADED INTO TRAILERS TO HELP ENSURE THE PACKAGES DO NOT TIP OVER.

AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP, THEN TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. AFTER CLOSER INSPECTION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 1 (1-GAL) PLASTIC JUG POPPED COMPLETELY OFF OF THE RECEPTACLE, CAUSING THE SPILLAGE OF APPROX. 2 QTS. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL CUSHIONING AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 44 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).
A RESPONDER WAS CALLED TO A LEAKING PACKAGE. THE LEAKING PACKAGE AND ALL DEBRIS WERE TAKEN TO THE DMP AREA. ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING UPS DMP PROCEDURES.

column168: On August 18, 2016, R & L Carriers (ATL Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN3262, Activated Black Magic Plus, 8, II (PRO#447036894) release. According to Mr. Bowden, terminal personnel were moving freight out in the yard when 1-500 pound fiberboard drum fell off the pallet causing a release. Approximately 3 pounds of product was released to the asphalt yard. Contractors arrived onsite and have identified the release. The fiberboard drum has been up-righted and the released material cleaned and neutralized. Cleanup and transfer has been completed at this time. The material was transferred to a 55 gallon poly open top drum and the waste has been placed into a 55 gallon poly open top drum.

Contractor also indicated that the drum was no longer leaking. Contractor over-packed the damaged drum into a 85 gallon metal drum for salvage. Contractor will stage the drum on site.

column168: While unloading the skid of material directly in front of the affected drum was taken from the truck. column168: during transportation phase, Trimac Transportation experienced the reported released of approximately 8 liquid gallons of a UN2734 Amines, liquid, Corrosive, Flammable, NOS from a MC307 in Lafayette, LA. The report indicated that the release was being contained by site personnel into plastic pails. An Environmental contractor was dispatched and indicated that a valve fitting was loose (not even hand tight) and the teflon gasket is not holding and appears to be slightly ripped. The contractor has inspected the flange bolts and they were all tight. A replacement tanker was dispatched and the contractor trans-loaded the product without further incident. The released product was solidified, containerized and taken by the contractor for profiling and disposal. No drains, soils or waterways were impacted by this release
column169: More in-depth training of conducting pre-trips of equipment before transportation begins. Thorough PM inspections and testing of equipment prior to dispatching.

On August 8, 2016, at the R&L Carriers terminal in Dallas, TX a steel cylinder carrying 560 pounds of UN1977 refrigerated nitrogen arrived leaking.  The cylinder was leaking from a defective pressure gauge.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site to attempt to secure the cylinder and stop the release.  Upon inspection the contractor advised that they could not fix the damaged pressure gauge or stop the release. The contractor advised that tightening the gauge did not stop the release and they could not determine the exact cause of the release from the gauge.  The contractor isolated the cylinder near an open dock door and allowed the cylinder to empty.  Once the cylinder was completely empty it was left on site for R&L personnel to manage.

column168: On 08/03/2016, a 55 gallon poly drum of UN3266 Zep Morado Super Cleaner arrived at the R&L Carriers terminal in Aurora, CO laying on its side and leaking. The drum had not been properly secured prior to shipping and fell over during transit.  The drum leaked approximately .5 gallons of material through an unsecured bung cap on its top. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the release to clean the impacted area and secure the leaking bung cap.  The environmental contractor cleaned and neutralized the released material. All waste was taken offsite by the contractor and the drum of material was left on site for R&L personnel to manage.

column168: Driver began to unload when approximately 10 gallons of unleaded spilled out of the vapor line on the consignee's tank. Due to spill, product was released into the storm drain and environmental team had to be called in to help with cleanup.
column169: Because driver is not familiar with consignee's tank, the consignee must be aware of how much product will fit into the tank.  Driver took a stick reading before unloading, showing there was plenty of room in the tank so the driver began to unload.  Because there was not enough room in the tank, product began to come out of the vapor recovery line.  Better communication between driver and consignee will help prevent this incident from reoccurring.

After unloading, our driver removed the hose from the consignee's tank and failed to fully closed the valve line on their tank, spilling about 10 gallons of Ferric Sulfate. The driver thought he closed the valve tight enough, once he realized product was coming from the valve line he tightened it and product stopped spilling out.
column169: This incident would have easily been avoided if the driver would have noticed that the valve was not closed all the way.  Proper training can help assure driver knows when the valve if fully closed.  The driver also should ask consignee if he or she is unsure if the valve is closed all the way.

column168: An alcohol like odor was reported in the Roseville Inbound yard. Upon investigation, Tank Car SHPX 208607 was found to be the source of the release. No shipper seal was applied to the combination housing.    The bottom outlet valve was in the closed position and releasing liquid from the less then tool tight cap. The cap was re-secured and the release stopped. The bottom outlet valve is defective.    The air valve was in the open position releasing vapor from the less then tool tight plug. The valve was closed and the plug secured which stopped the release.    The vacuum relief valve was engaged/open and releasing vapor. The engagement of the valve was from the air valve handle. The handle was bent and in the open position which was pushing down on the cap of the vacuum relief valve. The handle was moved and this stopped the release.      UPRR seal # 0000102 was applied to the combination housing.

ON FRIDAY JULY 29, 2016 SHIPPING CONTAINER BSIU2959075 WAS LOADED WITH 7 - 2000 POUND CHLORINE CONTAINERS AND 72-150 POUND CHLORINE CYLINDERS AT THE JCI JONES CHEMICALS, INC. FACILITY IN JACKSONVILLE, FLORIDA AND THEN PICKED UP THAT SAME DAY BY CROWLEY MAINE SERVICE, INC. AND TRANSPORTED TO THE JACKSONVILLE PORT AUTHORITY FOR OVERSEAS SHIPMENT. ON TUESDAY AUGUST 2, 2016 WHILE GETTING READY TO PREPARE THE SHIPPING CONTAINER FOR LOADING THE OVERSEAS VESSEL, A REPRESENTATIVE OF CROWLEY NOTIFIED JCI OF A POSSIBLE ODOR COMING FROM THE SHIPPING CONTAINER. UPON EVALUATION AND INVESTIGATION BY JCI, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE OF THE HAD DEVELOPED A PIN HOLE LEAK IN THE BOTTOM OF THE CYLINDER THAT RESULTED IN THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE 150 POUND CYLINDER BEING RELEASED TO THE ATMOSPHERE. WE BELIEVE THAT THE RELEASE OCCURRED SOMETIME BETWEEN JULY 29, 2016 WHEN THE SHIPPING CONTAINER ARRIVED AT THE JACKSONVILLE PORT AUTHORITY AND AUGUST 2, 2016 WHEN THE ODOR WAS FIRST DISCOVERED BUT DO NOT KNOW THE EXACT TIME OR DURATION OF THE RELEASE. GIVEN THAT THE CYLINDER WAS ALREADY EMPTY THOUGH, THERE WERE NO MITIGATING EFFORTS CONDUCTED.
column169: THE SUBJECT CYLINDER WAS CURRENTLY ‘IN HEAT!” WITH ITS LAST 50-YEAR HYDROSTATIC TEST DATE BEING SEPTEMBER 2012. PRIOR TO FILLING THE CYLINDER, JCI CONDUCTED A THOROUGH INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL INSPECTION OF ANY TYPE WITHIN OR ON THE BOTTOM OF THE CYLINDER. THE CYLINDER WAS FILLED WITH EXACTLY 150 POUNDS OF CHLORINE. A PROPER SCALE CHECK HEIGHT/WEIGHT TEST WAS PERFORMED THE MORNING IN WHICH THE CYLINDER WAS FILLED AND THERE WERE NO ISSUES WITH THE SCALE. THE CYLINDER PRIOR TO BEING FILLED WITH THE CURRENT TARE HEIGHT BEING 85 POUNDS VERSUS OF THE ORIGINAL TARE WEIGHT OF 86 POUNDS WHICH IS WELL WITHIN THE 5 TOLERANCE LEVEL. THE VALVE OF THE CYLINDER WAS ALSO INSPECTED AND TESTED PRIOR TO THE CONTAINER BEING FILLED WITH NO PROBLEMS NOTED. AN INSPECTION OF THE CYLINDER AFTER THE RELEASE DID NOT SHOW ANY ISSUES WITH THE CYLINDER OTHER THAN THE PIN HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF IT. THE CYLINDER WAS FREE OF EXCESSIVE MOISTURE, WATER AND FERRIC CHLORIDE BUILDUP, AND THE BOTTOM PORTION OF THE CYLINDER WAS DRY AND SMOOTH. THE ENTIRE BOTTOM PORTION OF THE CYLINDER WAS TAPPED ON WITH A HAMMER TO CHECK THE INTEGRITY OF IT AND THE TEST CONFIRMED THAT THE REMAINING AREA OF THE BOTTOM OF THE CYLINDER WAS INTACT AND SOLID WHICH LEADS US TO BELIEVE THAT THE PIN HOLE WAS A LOCALIZED SPOT ON THE CYLINDER.

column168: Driver rolled up liquid hose following delivery of anhydrous ammonia. Pressure increased in hose and hydrostat popped but did not reset. Driver smelled ammonia and observed a small vapor cloud. Driver opened liquid line valve to allow pressure to release into truck tank. Duration of release was estimated at ten seconds. Driver covered hydrostat with wet towel to mitigate smell.
column169: 1) Review proper procedures from start to finish with our driver to ensure that his understanding is complete.  2) Review this incident with all drivers.  3) Review our SOP to determine if additional steps concerning opening and closing the liquid line valve after delivery are required.  4) If our SOP is modified, review those modifications with all drivers.

Tanker was transported and dropped off by Smith Systems Transportation at Veolia's 10-day in transit facility in Henderson, CO. Veolia received it and placed it in containment. During daily inspections an employee noticed the a leak from the tanker and immediately contacted his supervisor & EH&S Manager. The hazardous material was removed from the tanker and loaded into a different tank.  The spill was cleaned up and the tanker was cleaned and sent to the shop for service. The report from the shop was: "Removed skin in front of rear subframe to locate a leak in the shell in tank. Welded cracks at rear of tank by rear ring channel, at rear of valve sump, and at left side of front ring channel on rear. Repaired leak at the ball valve thread on pop off valve. Replaced gasket at dome lid. Reinstalled skin after welding cracks at left front channel on rear suspension."
column169: Veolia reported the issues to Smith System and advised to do more frequent tanker inspections. The Smith System driver should have done a better pre & post vehicle inspection.

column168: A few things I'd like to call out.  The spill quantity and unit of measurement wouldn't let me put anything other than zero, not sure if there is some glitch.  Also I wasn't sure what to put under the admitted vs non-admitted.  Here is why.  Our driver (Donnie)went to the delivery area and met with the plant operator.  The operator indicated that he couldn't open the cap on the valve on the customer fill line.  Our driver looked at it and told the operator it should come open and he pulled on the valve.  The cap popped off in his hand and there was some pressure behind the cap which sprayed a mist out on the right side of his face, on his right hand, and abdomen.  He was wearing his hard hat with face shield (only half way down however), goggles, long pants, long sleeve shirt, and boots.  He was taken to the safety shower immediately and was in there for one hour.  He was then taken to the hospital and was kept there for about a day but they communicated to him that they were keeping him for a day just for observation.  He had first degree burns on the impacted areas and was given an antibiotic ointment. He has updated us twice since then that he is doing fine now.
column169: The driver admitted he was complacent and should have had the full PPE on (acid hood, chemical suit, chemical boots) required for unloading this prior to tampering with any valves.  He is going through retraining prior to moving any other loads on this dedicated account.

column168: AT 2018 HRS ON 8/1/2016, A KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) EMPLOYEE NOTICED THAT TANK CAR GATX 37572, LOCATED IN THE ALEXANDRIA,LA RAIL YARD, HAD DRIED LADING ON ITS SIDES. THE CAR ALSO HAD A SLIGHT ODOR, BUT DID NOT APPEAR TO BE ACTIVELY LEAKING. GATX 37572 WAS SET OUT FOR EVALUATION. THE KCS ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER. THE SHIPPER, BOISE PACKAGING, CONTACTED KCS ON 8/2/2016 AND DISPATCHED AN EMPLOYEE TO INVESTIGATE THE CAR THAT MORNING. UPON ARRIVAL, THE BOISE PACKAGING EMPLOYEE DID NOT FIND THE CAR TO BE ACTIVELY LEAKING, BUT OBSERVED A THIN LINE (6-8 INCHES WIDE) OF DRIED RESIDUE RUNNING PARTIALLY DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR. AFTER CLIMBING ON TOP OF THE CAR, THE BOISE PACKAGING EMPLOYEE OBSERVED A SMALL AMOUNT OF DRIED RESIDUE AROUND THE DOME WITH A SMALL PORTION RUNNING LENGTH WISE UP AND DOWN THE CAR. THIS WAS VISIBLE APPROXIMATELY 2 FEET IN BOTH DIRECTIONS FROM THE DOME. THE EMPLOYEE REMOVED THE SAFETY SEAL AND UNBOLTED THE MANWAY TO INSPECT THE GASKET. THE GASKET WAS FOUND TO BE INTACT, BUT A NEW GASKET WAS INSTALLED AS A PRECAUTION. THE MANWAY BOLTS WORE RETIGHTENED, AND A NEW SAFETY SEAL INSTALLED. THE RESIDUE WAS THEN CLEANED OFF THE CAR WITH DEGREASER AND WATER. ONCE ON THE GROUND THE LOWER THE OTHER CLOSURES WERE CHECKED FOR TIGHTNESS.     FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED TO THE CARRIER AS "BULK" SHIPMENT (I.E. ONE CAR LOAD), THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THE QUANTITY RELEASED.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (AKA PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS) THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSES OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS (PLEASE DIRECT YOU ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEARLY KSC RAILWAY PO BOX 219335 KANSAS CITY MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP:// NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

column168: Clean Harbors driver was transporting a tanker load of Waste Flammable liquids nos (Acetone/Xylene) to a rail spur to be off-loaded into a rail car.  Upon arriving at the rail yard the driver notice a stain on the side of the tanker coming from the dome area on top of the tanker.  The driver immediately wiped down the side of the tanker and then checked the dome securement devices to see if they were properly secured.  Each closure on the dome was tightly closed.  The contents in the tanker was off loaded into the rail car.  The gasket was inspected and was found to be flatten on one side.  The gasket was replaced.
column169: Reminded employees who are responsible for loading tankers that when the dome area is secured that the closure devices are secured in a star pattern and the devices are equally tighten.

column162: SVP HEALTH SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: Upon arrival at the Clean Harbors Waste Water Treatment Plant in Cleveland, OH the driver reported to plant personnel an strong odor emitting from the rear of the trailer. Plant personnel observed a yellow liquid and yellow staining on the rear of the trailer and tailgate. After consulting with Health and Safety and performing an air test, Level C PPE was donned and the trailer was unloaded. The source of the leak was discovered to be an IBC containing an acid solution. The top bung of the IBC had become dislodged during transport allowing the material contained within to splash onto the roof, walls and floor of the trailer as well as onto adjacent packages. A weak lime slurry solution was mixed and used to neutralize the acid on the walls and roof as well as the free liquid on the floor. The clean up material was collected and placed in the plants treatment process for disposal. No injuries were sustained.
column169: Drivers will be counselled on incident reporting requirements and container closure requirements. Warehouse employees will be counselled on container closure and load securement standards for IBC's.

On August 30, 2016,  R & L Carriers (ATL Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN1992, Entegrate IC3410, 3 (6.1), III (PRO#663539022) release. According to Mr. Hart, terminal personnel were unloading a trailer (OA4373) from the KAN terminal, when 2-350 gallon metal totes appeared to be leaking. Approximately 6 ounces of product was released to the tote and trailer floor. The totes are not leaking from a structural failure but rather from the vent caps. It was determined that the totes are fitted with venting caps that were the source of the release. The caps were taken off, cleaned and secured back on. All of the release material was wiped up and containerized in a 5 gallon pail. The rest of the totes in the trailer were assessed for signs of venting or leaking as well.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: At approximately 12:00 PST on 8/3/16, the LTCX 1919 was found leaking liquid argon from the valve cabinet while at the BNSF Watson railyard.  The car was isolated and BNSF Hazmat responders were dispatched to inspect and mitigate the release.  BNSF responders assessed the cabinet and determined liquid to be leaking from the threaded cap on the liquid line.  The valves were inspected and found to be what appeared to be in the closed position but were noted to be frozen.  Responders were able to tighten the cap which stopped the visual and audible release from the car.  There were no environmental impacts as the argon vaporized and dissipated.  The LTCX 1919 was placed on an inspection track with a hold applied.  Praxair was contacted and requested for a car technician to inspect the car prior to further movement.  On 8/4/16, a Praxair Technician inspected the car, replaced the liquid line cap gasket and secured the car.  No defects with the valve were noted or observed by the technician. Release volume is an estimate only based upon observations and information received by field personnel.
column169: The shipper was notified and advised of the release.  The shipper should review inspection and securement procedures.  All fittings and appliances should be closed and tool tight to ensure releases do not occur while in transportation.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: On 8/4/16 received notification from Hub personnel at BNSF Los Angeles that unit CAIU 808452 was leaking a clear liquid from under middle of the container floor upon deramping from the railcar. During unloading Hub personnel also noticed this unit had a leaning condition, making it unsafe to move in its condition. In the interest of safety, this unit was placed on hold from OG and was placed on the ground pending interior inspection of the cargo. WB showed unit to be loaded with hazardous materials, for safety reasons United Pumping Services was called out to asses the spilled product and to test the leaking material to determine if it was hazardous or nonhazardous.    Interior inspection found unit to be loaded with a mix freight of shrinkwrapped palletized pales, case products and two large IBC totes, stowed two rows wide with a partial second layer. A rear bull board was applied as a form of rear door securement, however there were several lateral voids that did not have any form of securement and resulted in some of the cargo to shift towards the left sidewall and creating a leaning condition. The responder found the leak to have been coming from a damaged pallet loaded with 5 gallon pails of a concentrated chlorinated bleach, a class 8 hazardous material  UN1791. Approximately 10 gallons of product spilled due to one of the nails from the damaged pallet puncturing holes on two 5 gallon pails, with approximately 1 gallon of product spilling on the ground.     United Pumping Services was able to clean up the spilled product and remediate all of the affected areas, the cargo had to be adjusted and secured in order for this unit to be placed onto a chassis and moved away from the trackside where it was placed. This unit was released for safe OG at  the drivers discretion.
column169: The Shipper should review loading and securement practices to ensure that similar types of incidents do not occur in the future.

column168: Third Party observed suspected product on side of car during transportation.      Inspection of car by contracted responder revealed product under protective housing, loose threaded connection between vapor valve and mounting plate: interference between vapor valve handle and vacuum relief device; and inadequate spring pressure on pressure relief device.    Vapor valve tightened.  Pressure allowed to reduce on car and leak ceased.  Car set out at next station for repair by car owner.    The duration of the release is unknown and the amount of release is estimated at less than 6 liquid pounds or approximately one gallon.  No evidence found that indicates any product reached the ground.    X-2016090078: Third Party observed suspect product on side of car during transportation.    Inspection of car by contracted responder revealed alcohol odor on top of car and under protective housing.  Audible indications of pressure/vapor release through vacuum relief device.  Pressure allowed to reduce on car and vapor release ceased. Car set out at next station for repair by car owner.   The duration of the release is unknown and the amount of release is estimated at less than 6 liquid pounds or approximately one gallon. No evidence found that indicates any product reached the ground.

column168: On 8/15/2016 at approximately 1542 hours, CSX Transportation personnel reported the discovery of product on the exterior of tank car NATX 364171 in the CSX Brooklyn Junction Yard, New Martinsville, WV. All required regulatory notifications were immediately made, and CSX Transportation contracted with Specialized Professional Services, Inc, (SPSI) from Washington, PA, to respond and investigate.    Upon arrival SPSI determined the point of release to be the top mounted liquid line ball valve - thread interface into the valve assembly plate was found less than hand tight, resulting in the release of hazardous materials. SPSI secured the release by proper application of the valve to tool-tightness, and removed all material on the exterior of the car.    The shipper has been advised the package is no longer qualified for transportation without an OTMA or requalification testing. No additional follow up is expected by CSX Transportation.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 08/26/2016 at 11:45, personnel in the CSXT Uceta Yard discovered TCIX 300099, a loaded tank car of Methanol, leaking from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper SNF Holding Company, the Florida State Watch Office (report number 2016-6531), and the NRC (report number 1157395) were notified.  CHEMTREC report number  2016-0826-00150).  Hulls Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car to have three out of six manway bolts less than tool tight.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (Stacy Hamlin, phone number 912-880-8066).  Contractor personnel tightened the manway bolts and noted the product had evaporated from the top of the car.  The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.  This incident did not require a special switching move or a 7.1.      Cause Code: 200  NARRI: 80

column168: forklift damage , skid was clipped with metal rack while being moved with a forklift     approx. 1 liter or less  released .     Clean up with HHAZCHEM emergency response company as a precaution.   Staff keep away from the area of leakage.     Used 2016 ERG for guidance. The usa emergency response number was missing a digit .  The " for Europe" emergency response # worked and  SDS was obtained.
column169: Handling company AGI gave this corrective action :     Storage of large amount of DGR will be done in a ULD storage manner to place the DGR out of normal DGR storage areas and away from forklift traffic.  This would also eliminate double forklift handling.    Minimal forklift usage, use of pallet jacks whenever possible.    When a forklift is needed to move DGR , AGI supervision with a second AGI agent will be used.

On 8/26/16, in Mogadore, Ohio, during the course of routine business it was discovered that a pallet of 5 gallon plastic jerry cans of UN3103 Trigonox 101 was leaking in the back of an R&L Carriers trailer.  The damaged containers released approximately 1 cup of material to the trailer floor.  No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release and over pack any damaged containers.  Upon breaking down the pallet of containers it was discovered that 19 5 gallon containers had defective and cracked lids.  The damaged containers were overpacked into 7 55 gallon poly drums and labeled with all applicable shipping information.  The contractor transported the over packed material to an R&L Carriers terminal in Columbiana, Ohio for R&L personnel to manage.  All waste generated was taken offsite by the contractor for disposal.

column168: On August 17th, 2016, a Hydrite Chemical Co. delivery was made to Miller Electric on behalf of Americo Chemical Co., our customer.        Hydrite manufactures the bulk chemical for our customer, and delivers bulk products for them.    The order of Americo Spray Clean 1117B at Miller Electric was for 9,990 gallons, and in this case 1,085 gallons were made and loaded for delivery to Miller electric.   The actual batch size for this load is typically over the order quantity due to adjustments in manufacturing.   The actual batch size may vary.    Our driver, Jerry Golata, arrived at the Miller site, and was directed to dock 17.   Jerry hooked up compartment #2 to the unloading connection.   Tom H. from Miller Electric came out to the unloading area.   Jerry asked Tom to sign the Bill of Lading to verify the load and delivery.   Tom looked at the connection and signed the BOL.   (The pre/unload safety checks on the BOL stated 1. the product is what was ordered, 2. there is adequate capacity available in the storage tank, 3. the hoses are connected to the correct inlet, and 4. the valves are in the correct position.)  Jerry Golata then signed both copies of the BOL and put the customer copy of the signed BOL in a nearby plastic tube on the fence.      Tom told Jerry to grab a radio and ask for Tom if he needed anything and then he went into the building and did not return.   After a while, Jerry connected the air hose to the trailer and the pump on the tractor, opened the valves slowly and began the transfer.   After a while, Jerry went to the overhead door to see if he could check on the tank, but the overhead door was locked.   About 30 minutes later, the hose made a slight shake indicating it was empty, so Jerry closed the internal and then external valves.   He then closed the valve at the building and shut off the air to pump the trailer.   He bled the pressure off of the hose and disconnected the air from the trailer and tractor.   Then he released the pressure from compartment #2.   He capped off the hoses and put them away along with the bleeder bucket.    Jerry walked around the truck to inspect before he left.   He went to the northwest end of the lot to fill out the log book and customer information sheet and left around 8:00 AM.   At the time he left, Jerry was unaware that the storage tank had been overfilled and that material had leaked out of the vent and into the containment area.   It had also splattered on the overhead door.     Miller Electric found the release some time between 8:00 and 8:20 AM, and contacted Americo Chemical Products Co.    Americo contacted Hydrite sales (Jerry Colarassi), who contacted Ryan Griffin, Operations Manager at Hydrite Chemical Co., to notify him that the storage tank had overflowed.   The material was in containment and impacted an overhead door.    There were no injuries or releases to the environment.   Hydrite called in Northshore Environmental services to respond.   In the meantime, folks at Mille
column169: Hydrite Chemical Co. lists both the order quantity and the actual quantity of a delivery on the BOL.    Many of the batches are made to order at our plant, and loaded directly into a tanker.   When possible, we contact the customer prior to shipment to verify if they can accept the full volume, but on off hours this may not be possible since the delivery and driver times may be when the customer is not operating.   In order to address this, we have pre/unload safety checks on the BOL that include customer check of adequate capacity available in the storage tank(s).    We have reviewed this overfill event with our drivers.   Our customers must have adequate capacity to receive our loads.   Although written on Bills of Lading, our drivers will now highlight to the customer when the delivered quantity exceeds the order quantity, and ask them to verify that they have adequate capacity to receive that amount before they sign the pre/unload safety check and we unload.  We often schedule a bit more than the order, since we may have transfer losses.   Recognize that each foot of hose can hold nearly 2 gallons, so these must be considered in scheduling.        We need customers to manage their storage tanks and know the available capacity.   Companies may have gauges, level meters, and some have controllers that can be used to prevent overfills.

column168: Checking out at the shipper's exit gate, our driver noticed product fumes.  The shipper and our driver inspected the CTMV and did not find any product release.  Our driver departed for the consignee, stopping in Anna, Ohio for fuel.  At the fuel station, our driver noticed product fumes, and checked the CTMV, finding no release.  Our driver departed the fuel station, but thought he heard the pressure relief valve cycling.  He pulled over on the highway on-ramp to re-inspect the CTMV.  Our driver observed a release at the front bulkhead, placed a bucket under the CTMV to contain the hazmat, and called our 24/7 call center for assistance.  We dispatched a hazmat contractor.  Shortly after, the CTMV failed catastrophically.  The tank shell burst, releasing the contents to the on-ramp pavement and surrounding soil.  We called local and county fire and hazmat.    Local fire department crews and hazmat teams arrived, followed shortly by the hazmat contractor.  The incident commander mitigated the effects of the release by cordoning off the area, which included closing the on-ramp.  Subsequently, the impacted pavement was cleaned, and the impacted soils were removed.  Damages are not available at this time.  We will file a supplemental report when damages have been determined.    Quality Carriers Reference: Event 61363.

column168: On 8/31/2016 at the R&L Carriers Terminal in Chicago, Illinois a 55 gallon steel drum of UN1866 Macopol resin was punctured by a fork lift while unloading a trailer. The damaged drum was over packed into an 85 gallon steel drum and labeled with all applicable shipping information.  The over pack drum was left on site for R&L personnel to mange.  No waste was generated during the response.

A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation.  A labpack drum containing one pint glass bottle of solution fell 1' from storage pallet onto warehouse floor into containment.  Inner glass bottle leaked.  The 5 gallon labpack drum also leaked from its lid while drum was on its side.  Approximately 3 ounces of material leaked onto floor.  Drum was immediately up-righted.  Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised container into a suitable salvage drum. Spilled material was cleaned with absorbent.  Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required  specifications.  It is suggested the officer should provide its staff with additional training on the correct preparation of labpacks for transportation.

column168: ON AUGUST 10, 2016 AT APPROXIMATELY 10:40 TRAIN S53910 DERAILED RAIL CARS 58-81 ON THE CONSIST WHILE TRAVELING SOUTH AT MILEPOST OKC 40.45 AT WOODSON ROAD IN FALMOUTH KENTUCKY. INITIAL REPORTS WERE THAT MULTIPLE HAZMAT PACKAGES WERE INVOLVED. A LOADED TANK OF SULFURIC ACID TILX 101201 WAS LAYING ON IT SIDE ACROSS THE GRADE CROSSING WITH THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING INTO A BROKEN TELEPHONE POLE. THE DERAILMENT TRIGGERED A LOCAL EVACUATION OF 585 INDIVIDUALS AS WELL AS AN ADDITIONAL 1,800 TO BE SHELTERED IN PLACE. ADDITIONALLY STATE ROUTE 27 WAS CLOSED DUE TO SAFETY CONCERNS FROM THE DERAILMENT. AFTER FURTHER ASSESSMENT BY CSX HAZMAT AND THE COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM IT WAS DETERMINED THAT NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS RELEASED FROM THE DERAILMENT. THIS DOT 5800.1 REPORT IS BEING FILED DUE TO THE EVACUATION AND STATE ROAD CLOSURES.

column168: A 330 gal poly tote containing UN1760 corrosive liquid released 5 gals in a trailer from the loose lid falling off. Hazmat contractors arrived onsite and re-secured the tote cap and cleaned up the release.

UTLX 209899 was noted releasing vapor during a routine inspection by an FRA inspector in the Albuquerque yard. BNSF responders from Belen were notified and responded to investigate the release. The vacuum relief valve was noted as the source of the vapor release. BNSF HazMat responders removed the defective vacuum relief valve and installed a 2 1/2" plug with Teflon tape.  The shipper applied for an OTMA-3 to move the car to destination for offloading.
column169: The shipper must ensure that the valves on the tank car are secure and intact prior to loading.  The vacuum relief valve is one of those components that need to be evaluated for proper operation and o-ring integrity prior to loading and prior to releasing for transport.

column168: Our driver pulled onto shipper scales after loading for final inspection of the CTMV and noticed a leak from the external valve cap. The shipper initially determined the leak to be water between the internal and external valves, but after a 15 minute waiting period with the drip continuing, shipper determined that product was leaking from the internal valve onto the scales. The driver immediately used a collection bucket to contain the leak. Shipper decided to transfer the product to another CTMV.     Upon further inspection from a mechanic, no issue was found with the internal valve on the CTMV and the leak could not be replicated during testing.       Event # 61424

column42: ACETIC ACID, GLACIAL OR ACETIC ACID SOLUTION, WITH MORE THAN 80 PERCENT ACID, BY MASS
column168: ON 10 AUGUST 2016 AT APPROXIMATELY 11:46AM, A BAE SYSTEMS OPERATOR AT AREA A BEGAN FILLING A GLACIAL ACETIC ACID RAIL TANKER CAR (#18602) FOR OUTBOUND TRANSFER TO THE AREA B FACILITY. THE TRANSFER OF ACETIC ACID IS ACCOMPLISHED BY PUMPING MATERIAL FROM TANK 4 IN TANK FARM 27 INTO A RAIL TANKER CAR STAGED AT THE TANK FARM 27 LOADING STATION. PRIOR TO THE TRANSFER, THE INITIAL LEVEL READING BEING MONITORED BY THE OPERATOR IN THE CONTROL ROOM SHOWED 209.74 INCHES OF GLACIAL ACETIC ACID IN FEED TANK 4. THE TARGETED DRAWDOWN ESTABLISHED BY THE OPERATOR WAS 184 INCHES, SINCE ONE INCH OF ACID DELIVERED FROM FEED TANK 4 IS 6,504 LBS AND THE RAIL TANK CAR'S CAPACITY IS 27 INCHES OR 175,608 LBS. OF GLACIAL ACETIC ACID.     DURING THE TRANSFER, THE OPERATOR STEPPED AWAY FROM THE LOADING STATION FOR A BRIEF PERIOD TO FILL OUT THE OUTBOUND SHIPMENT PAPERWORK IN THE NEARBY TANK FARM 27 CONTROL ROOM. THERE IS NOT A DIRECT LINE OF SIGHT FROM THE TANK FARM 27 ROOM TO THE RAIL CAR LOADING STATION. WHEN THE OPERATOR ARRIVED INSIDE THE CONTROL ROOM, THE DISTRIBUTED CONTROL SYSTEM READOUT SHOWED 195 INCHES IN TANK 5. THE OPERATOR STATED DURING AN INTERVIEW AS PART OF THE INVESTIGATION PROCESS THAT HE HAD PLANNED TO COMPLETE THE REQUIRED PAPERWORK, MONITOR THE THE DISTRIBUTED CONTROL SYSTEM (DCS) READOUT INSIDE THE CONTROL ROOM, AND RETURN TO THE RAIL TANK CAR WHEN THE LEVEL IN TANK HAD REACHED 190 INCHES. WHEN THE LEVEL REACHED 190 INCHES THE OPERATOR OPENED THE DOOR TO EXIT THE CONTROL ROOM AND NOTICED THE RAIL-CAR OVERFLOWING.
column169: 1) SAFETY TO PERFORM JOB HAZARD ANALYSIS (JHA) AND ASSIST DEPARTMENT IN ESTABLISHMENT SAFE, DEDICATED OBSERVATION POINT WHERE OPERATOR WILL MONITOR RAIL-CAR LOADING. REQUIRE TWO PEOPLE FOR THE LOADING/UNLOADING OF RAIL-CARS OR TRUCKS. ONE PERSON TO BE AT DEDICATED OBSERVATION POINT MAINTAINING LINE OF SIGHT OF THE RAIL-CAR AT ALL TIMES DURING LOADING/UNLOADING.     2) RELOCATE OR PURCHASE A FLOW CONTROL DEVICE THAT WILL CUT OFF THE PUMP ONCE THE SPECIFIED VOLUME OF MATERIAL HAS BEEN TRANSFERRED. THIS DEVICE TO BE INSTALLED ON THE 521 LOADING LINE AT AREA A.     3) ADDITIONAL OF SECONDARY TRANSFER PUMP KILL SWITCH AT DEDICATED OBSERVATION POINT.

column168: ON AUGUST 22, 2016, AT APPROXIMATELY 10:40AM, CDT A TRACTOR TRAILER OPERATED BY COWAN SYSTEMS, LLC (CS) WAS DRIVING AT THE ABOVE-REFERENCED LOCATION WHEN THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL, ROLLING THE TRACTOR-TRAILER OVER. AS A RESULT, THE SADDLE TANK BECAME DAMAGED, RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL TO THE ASPHALT SURFACES OF THE ROADWAY. THE CARGO INSIDE THE TRAILER BECAME DAMAGED RELEASING AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF POLYETHER-MODIFIED POLYSILOXANE (PMP) TO THE TRAILER INTERIOR AND ASPHALT SURFACES OF THE ROADWAY.     ON AUGUST 22, 2016, THE BALTIMORE CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT (BCFD), MARYLAND STATE POLICE (MSP), TED'S TOWING (TT), AND THE MARYLAND (HAZMAT) EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM (MERT) ARRIVED ON-SITE TO ESTABLISH TRAFFIC CONTROL OPERATIONS AND TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE. THE BCFD DEPLOYED GRANULAR ABSORBENTS AND SAND TO PREVENT MIGRATION OF THE DIESEL FUEL AND THE PMP. THE MSP ESTABLISHED TRAFFIC CONTROL OPERATIONS TO ENSURE PUBLIC SAFETY. THE MERT ASSESSED THE CARGO AND COLLECTED SIX (6) 55-GALLONS DRUMS OF PMP IN ORDER TO UPRIGHT THE TRACTOR-TRAILER. A CREW FROM TT COLLECTED ROAD DEBRIS AND BROUGHT THE TRACTOR-TRAILER UPRIGHT IN ORDER TO CLEAR THE ROADWAY.     ON AUGUST 22, 2016, AT APPROXIMATELY 12:51PM, CDT, MEG PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON-SITE. FOLLOWING AN ASSESSMENT OF THE SCENE, THEY NOTED APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL HAD BEEN RELEASED TO THE ASPHALT SURFACES OF THE ROADWAY AND PMP RELEASED TO THE INTERIOR OF THE TRAILER, AS WELL AS, THE ASPHALT SURFACES OF THE ROADWAY. MEG PERSONNEL DEPLOYED ADDITIONAL GRANULAR ABSORBENTS TO THE DIESEL FUEL AND PMP IMPACTED ASPHALT SURFACES AND WORKED IN WITH HAND TOOLS. MEG PERSONNEL COLLECTED THE DIESEL FUEL AND PMP IMPACTED SAND AND STAGED ON-SITE FOR DISPOSAL AT LATER DATE. MEG PERSONNEL COLLECTED ONE (1) 55-GALLON DRUM OF DIESEL FUEL AND PMP IMPACTED MATERIALS FOR TRANSPORT AND DISPOSAL. TT PERSONNEL THEN TOWED THE TRACTOR-TRAILER FROM THE INTERSTATE TO A NEARBY ROAD TO CLEAR THE ROADWAY. MEG PERSONNEL DONNED LEVEL C PPE AND ENTERED THE TRAILER TO ASSESS AND REMEDIATE THE TRAILER INTERIOR. MEG PERSONNEL STABILIZED THE TRAILER WITH ABSORBENT BOOMS AND GRANULAR ABSORBENTS. TT PERSONNEL THEN TOWED THE TRACTOR-TRAILER TO THEIR TOW YARD. MEG PERSONNEL SECURED THE SITE AND SCHEDULED TO RETURN THE TWO YARD TO COLLECT THE PMP BY VACUUM TRUCK FOR DISPOSAL.     ON AUGUST 25, 2016, AT APPROXIMATELY 8:00AM, CDT, MEG PERSONNEL ARRIVED AT TOW YARD. MEG PERSONNEL TRANSFERRED THE PMO FROM THE DAMAGED TOTES INTO ONE (1) VACUUM TRUCK. THE EMPTY TOTES WERE THEN COLLECTED IN ONE (1) ROLL-OFF BOX FOR TRANSPORT AND DISPOSAL. MEG PERSONNEL SECURED THE SITE AND SCHEDULED TO COLLECT THE WASTE STAGED ON-SITE.     ON SEPTEMBER 1, 2016, MEG PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON-SITE, AND COLLECTED THE DIESEL FUEL AND PMP IMPACTED SAND FROM THE SITE. MEG PERSONNEL SECURED THE SITE AND DEMOBILIZED.

column25: REAGENT CHEMICAL + RESEARCH c/o BASF CORP
column168: On August 24, 2016, at 11:22 hours, a Transportation Manager at the CSXT Queensgate Terminal, Cincinnati, Ohio reported that a yard crew saw  RCRX 1259, a loaded tank car of UN1789,Hydrochloric acid leaking from the top of the tank car. Reportedly, there was product around the top and noticeable on the side of the tank car.. The tank car was located within the classification yard tracks and was isolated. The shipper, Reagent Chemicals, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2016-0824-00169. Environmental Management Specialists, a CSXT emergency response contractor and a CSX Hazardous Material Manager, was dispatched to the Queensgate Terminal. It was suspected due to a deteriorated portion of the tank car and evidence of acid in that location that there was a possible breach in the vapor space of the tank car just below the pressure housing flange where the weld attaches to the tank car. The shipper representative, KEVIN CALLAIS, was notified of the situation found and preparation was made for a possible transfer of the product. A temporary patch was put over the suspected area with a sealant caulk in order to safely move to an accessible location within the Terminal. During movement and after the tank car was placed in an accessible area it was checked and no visible product was found nor any hydrochloric vapors were evident. The entire flange assembly was wrapped in a plastic sheet to secure the area from impending rain.    Environmental Management Specialists, CSXT Hazmat Manager and a Reagent Chemical employee returned to the yard on August 25, 2016 to further inspect the tank car and determine if the tank shell was leaking. After further inspection hydrochloric acid was visible inside of the plastic sheeting which showed there was an issue with a component on the housing of the tank car. It was determined that the fill hole was improperly secured and that was the point of release. The fill hole was properly secured for transportation and the tank car was neutralized to remove any residue hydrochloric acid. The tank car was then released for transportation.  .  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100  Cause code:224

column168: On August 24th, 2016 at 11:39 hours, FRA Inspectors at CSXT Selkirk Yard discovered TAEX 2626, a residue tank car, last contained, Alcohols, N.O.S., UN1987, releasing vapors from around the manway cover, between swing bolts numbers 4 + 5. The tank car was isolated and the shipper of record was notified via CHMETREC, report #2016-08-24-00173. Mr. Sid DeCell. with Global Companies, LLC was notified of the incident. EP+S of Vermont, a CSXT emergency response contractor was dispatched, met with the FRA Inspectors at Selkirk Yard, and investigated the release point, EPSVT identified a misaligned manway cover nozzle gasket, the gasket was inspected and re-seated into the manway cover gasket groove, the manway cover was re-secured to be tool tight.  Mr. Sid DeCell, Global Companies, LLC was updated as to the situation found, and the corrective action taken to re-secure the manway cover.  TAEX 2626 was released for disposition.      Cause Code: 208  NARRI: 5(4+3+0) x (2+0) = 70

column168: Rail car UTLX 299018, a residue methanol car, derailed at approximately 1635 hours on 8/21 and damaged the bottom outlet valve and sheared bottom outlet nozzle bolts, removing the nozzle and secondary closure.      The extent of the damage to the valve was unknown and no product leakage was noted during re-railing activities.  A small amount of product was noted dripping from the damaged valve on the morning of 8/22.  Duration of the release is unknown, but it cannot exceed 18 hours.      Quantity of release is estimated at less than one gallon.  A bucket was used to capture the material until the valve could be plugged with expanding foam plug.  The car will be cleaned, purged and scrapped.

column168: At approximately 2300 hours on 8/22/2016 in the BNSF San Bernardino yard in San Bernardino, CA a security guard patrolling the area heard and saw evidence of a vapor release from tank car CWBX 2004 which was carrying a load of Propane (UN1075) STCC 4905421.  BNSF Hazmat Manager responded to the car and upon arrival found an active release in the form of vapor slightly hissing from the pressure relief valve.  Further examination and disassembly of the pressure relief valve revealed an improperly sized O-ring on the stem side of the movable valve.  The O-ring was replaced with the proper fitting O-ring and the car was monitored for any evidence of release.  Pressure was at 165 psi and held with no further release.  The following day, BNSF contractor United Pumping measured pressure, outage, and monitored for any evidence of release via use of CGI to detect LEL - no evidence of further release was found.  No remediation necessary, FRA Steven Wolfe was contacted for advice on movement of this car and whether or not OTMA would be required.  Wolfe replied indicating OTMA would not be needed if bubble leak test was performed.  Bubble leak test was performed by Union Tank Car on 9/13/2016 and car was released from hold status for furtherance and delivery.
column169: Shipper was notified of the incident.  Cars used in transportation of hazardous materials shipment must be properly equipped and have functioning valves, fittings, closures, and seals to prevent release.  In this case O-rings and mechanical functionality of pressure relief valve must be compliant and operational and should be inspected or evaluated prior to shipment to avoid release in transit.

column168: FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS MOVING FREIGHT FROM THE TRAILER @ ROSS EXPRESS NH LOADING DOCK AND HIT THE WRONG CONTROL LEVER. THIS ACTION CAUSED THE FORKS TO MOVE IN A WRONG DIRECTION, CAUSING THE FORKS TO HIT THE BOTTOM SIDE OF THE DRUM AND CREATE A HOLE. A SMALL AMOUNT OF HM PRODUCT LEAKED ONTO THE DOCK. FORKLIFT OPERATOR ACTED QUICKLY AND TURN THE DRUM UPRIGHT TO PREVENT MORE LIQUID FROM LEAKING OUT OF THE HOLE, THE DAMAGE AREA WAS TO THE BOTTOM THE SIDE OF THE DRUM. THE DOCK EMPLOYEE THEN REPORTED IT TO HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR WHO ALERTED ALL THE DOCK AND DRIVING EMPLOYEES TO EVACUATE THE AREA AND GO OUTSIDE FROM THE LOADING DOCK. THE SUPERVISOR SECURED THE LOCATION FROM RECEIVING ANYMORE TRUCK LOADS TO THE LOCATION. THE SUPERVISOR CHECK HIS SDS BOOK AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK THEN CALLED "BOSCAWEN, NH FIRE DEPARTMENT- CHIEF RAY FISHER TO ASSIST HIM TO WITH THE CLEANUP. THIS EVENT STARTED @ 12:20AMAND WAS CLEANED UP BY 2:15AM. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CLEARED HEALTH-WISE THE TWO EMPLOYEES WHO MADE CONTACT WITH THE LEAKING DRUM. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CLEANED UP THE HM PRODUCT THAT HAD LEAKED OUT OF THE DRUM AND WAS DISPOSING OF THE MATERIAL. THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN A SECURED AREA OF THE YARD CONED OFF TO KEEP PERSONNEL AWAY FROM THE DRUM UNTIL THE COMPANY WAS ABLE TO HAVE A COMPANY COME TO THE FACILITY TO REMOVE THE DAMAGED DRUM WITH PRODUCT STILL IN THE DRUM. ROSS EXPRESS WAS ABLE TO HIRE CLEAN HARBOR TO REMOVE THE DRUM AND PRODUCT ON 9/2/16 AND IT WAS RETURN AND RECEIVED BY THE SHIPPER OF THE PRODUCT- SERVICE CHEMICAL, LLC, NORTH ANDOVER, MA.
column169: FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS COUNSELED ON THE PROPER USE OF FORKLIFT EQUIPMENT AT OUR COMPANY THROUGH OUR SAFETY AND ACCOUNTABILITY PROGRAM. THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR IS A NEW EMPLOYEE THAT COMPLETED HIS FORKLIFT TRAINING CERTIFICATION ON-9/6/2016.

column168: THE DRIVE LOADED #2 HEATING OIL INTO THE CARGO TANK AT IRVING OIL IN REVERE MA. THE PRODUCT WAS DESTINED FOR BARRE VT. WHILE THE LOAD WAS IN TRANSIT, THE DRIVER STOPPED IN PORTMOUTH, NH TO TAKE A BREAK. BEFORE LEAVING PORTSMOUTH, HE WALKED AROUND THIS TRUCK AND TRAILER TO DO A VISUAL INSPECTION. HE NOTICED A DAMP AREA NEAR THE LANDING GEAR UPPER SUPPORT BRACE. UPON EXAMINATION HE FOUND IT TO BE FUEL OIL. HE REPORTED HIS FINDINGS TO COMPANY OFFICIALS. THEY TRIED TO RE-ROUTE THE LOAD TO A CLOSER DESTINATION TO GET IT UNLOADED SOONER. NO OPTIONS WERE AVAILABLE, SO HE CONTINUED TO BARRE, VT. UPON ARRIVAL THE DAMPNESS WAS NOW A SLOW DRIP. DRIPS WERE CONTAINED IN A SPILL BUCKET WHILE UNLOADING. ESTIMATED LEAK DURING TRANSPORT WAS LESS THAN A GALLON. WE BROUGHT THE CARGO TANK TO OUR MAINTENANCE FACILITY IN HAMPDEN, ME FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIRS. THE WAS FOUND TO HAVE A CRACKED WELD IN THE TANK WALL.
column169: THE LEAK WAS FROM A STRUCTURAL WELD CRACK. THE DRIVER RESPONDED AS TRAINED. WE HAVE SINCE FORMED A LIST OF ADDITIONAL CONTACT PERSONNEL AT IRVING OIL THAT WILL HELP US RE-ROUTE A LEAKING TRAILER TO CLOSER LOCATIONS, TO PREVENT HIGHER QUANTITIES OF LEAKAGE.

column168: ON AUGUST 29, 2016, AT APPROXIMATELY 0145 CDT, A CTL TRANSPORTATION (CTL) TANKER UNIT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE RELEASING SULFURIC ACID FROM A WELD POINT ON AN EXTERNAL VALVE. THE MATERIAL WAS BEING RELEASED INTO A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA AT THE FACILITY. ON SITE PERSONNEL BEGAN TO GRAVITY TRANSFER THE SULFURIC ACID INTO ANOTHER TANKER ON SITE. IT WAS REQUESTED TO HAVE A CREW MOBILIZE TO PUMP TRANSFER INTO AN ALTERNATE TANKER ON SITE AND ADDRESS THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA. THE CREW FROM SWS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (SWS) ARRIVED ON SITE. CREW MEMBERS STATED THAT FACILITY PERSONNEL HAD COMPLETED THE TRANSFER OF THE SULFURIC ACID FROM THE DAMAGED TANKER INTO AN ALTERNATE TANKER ON SITE. CREW MEMBERS DEPLOYED A NEUTRALIZING AGENT TO THE SULFURIC ACID-IMPACTED CONCRETE AREA AND COLLECTED ALL WASTE INTO ONE (1) 55-GALLON DRUM FOR TRANSPORT AND DISPOSAL. WITH THE SITE RETURNED TO PRE-RELEASE CONDITIONS, SWS PERSONNEL COLLECTED ALL TOOLS AND EQUIPMENT AND DEMOBILIZED FROM THE SITE.

PACKAGE TOSSED FROM UNLOAD DEVICE TO IRREGULARS SLIDE. PACKAGE LANDED UPSIDE DOWN AND BROKE BOTTLES SEAL. CONTENTS RAN DOWN SLIDE ON TO UNLOAD FLOOR AND UNDER IRREGULARS SLIDE AND IRREGULARS BELT. AREA WAS SECURED WITH CAUTION TAPE. DECISION TREE WAS FOLLOWED AND SODIUM BI-CARB WAS DEPLOYED UNTIL WE RAN OUT. 1.5 BOXES WERE USED AND WAS INSUFFICIENT TO SOLIDIFY THE SPILL. DISTRICT SPILL COORDINATOR WAS NOTIFIED AND THE DECISION WAS MADE TO CONTACT AN OUTSIDE SERVICE DUE TO THE AMOUNT OF MATERIALS TO BE CONTAINED AND THAT WE WERE NOW OUT OF SODIUM BI-CARB.

column168: THE INCIDENT OCCURRED DURING THE LOADING OF DRUMS TO AN OUTBOUND TRAILER. AN OPEN TOP POLY 55 DRUM FELL OFF THE PALLET WHILE IT WAS BEING TRANSPORTED ON A PALLET AND BEGAN TO LEAK. ON-SITE PERSONNEL ASSISTED IN UPRIGHTING THE DRUM, HOWEVER, DURING THAT PROCESS, THE LID CAME OFF AND RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS TO THE LOADING AREA (ASPHALT PARKING LOT). AT NO TIME DID THIS MATERIAL GO OFF PROPERTY OR RELEASE TO LAND. ON-SITE PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY BEGAN CONTAINMENT OPERATIONS. THE MATERIAL WAS SUBSEQUENTLY CLEANED UP.
column169: IMPLEMENTED A POLICY TO NO LONGER PICK UP WASTE IN OPEN HEAD POLY DRUMS, RETRAINING OF PERSONNEL, IMPROVED OPERATING PROCEDURES.

column168: DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS OF A PALLET WITH 3 EMPTY DRUM AND 1 DRUM OF PRODUCT DAIRY BRITE, THE DAIRY BRITE DRUM SPILLED AT THE BOTTOM AND THE CONTENT SPILLED ON THE DOCK AND INTO THE LOWER TRACK WELL. WAREHOUSE SUPERVISION APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CONTAIN THE SPILL AND AREA WAS ISOLATED.
column169: PACKING CHANGE IS BEING EVALUATED TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

column168: AT 0700 HRS ON 8/25/16 IT WAS REPORTED THAT TANK CAR ACFX 94713 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN BEAUMOUNT YARD. THE ENVIRONMENTAL AND HAZMAT DEPARTMENT DISPATCHED A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE. THE LIQUID LINE CAP WAS FOUND TO BE CRACKED. ADDITIONALLY THE CAR WAS BEING SHIPPED UNDER PRESSURE, CONTRIBUTING TO THE LEAK. THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RELEASED THE PRESSURE TO STOP THE LEAK. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE DEFECT. A NEW LIQUID LINE CAP WAS OBTAINED BY THE SHIPPER WHO DEPLOYED THEIR OWN CONTRACTOR TO INSTALL THE NEW CAP ON THE TANK CAR. WITH THE CAR SECURE, THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION.       FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED TO THE CARRIER AS A "BULK" SHIPMENT (I.E. ONE CAR LOAD), THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THE QUANTITY RELEASED.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. column25: ELANCO C/O NOVARTIS ANIMAL HEALTH INC
column168: ONE DRUM DRUM OF UN3077 WAS TORN DURING IMPORT STORAGE . DAMAGE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER FORKLIFT HANDLING. THE TEAR CAUSED APPROX 1KG OF UN3077 ( SOLID) TO LEAK OUT OF THE CARTON.   THE LEAKAGE WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. THE 1 KG OF SPILLED UN3077 WAS PLACED INTO ANOTHER RECOVERY DRUM.   THE CONSIGNEE AGREED TO ACCEPT BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WITH THE REST OF THE IMPORT SHIPMENT.
column169: THE WAREHOUSE HANDLING COMPANY , AGI , PROVIDED CORRECTIVE ACTION AS FOLLOWS :     MUCH GREATER USAGE OF AUTOMATED LARGE SHIPMENT STORAGE SYSTEM. THE LARGE SHIPMENT WAS DIFFICULT TO STORE INTO THE NORMAL DGR IMPORT STORAGE AREA.    GREATER CARE WITH IMPORT DGR STORAGE, AVOID FORKLIFT WHEN POSSIBLE, IF FORKLIFT IS NEEDED THEN AGI MANAGEMENT MUST SUPERVISE TO ENSURE DGR SAFETY.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: THE HANDLING COMPANY, AGI, WAS MOVING A SLAVE DOLLY A FEW FEET BY PLACING THE FORKLIFT BLADE ON THE OPENING OF THE FORKLIFT HOLE OF THE SLAVE DOLLY. THE FORKLIFT HOLE WAS NOT USED FOR THE FORKLIFT BLADES.   THE FORKLIFT BLADE SLIPPED AND THE FORKLIFT BLADE FLIPPED UP AND DAMAGED ONE DRUM OF UN1263/ PAINT. A SMALL AMOUNT OF PAINT CAME OUT OF THE DRUM, BUT WAS VERY THICK SLOW TO LEAK. THE DAMAGE WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM ALONG WITH ANY CLEAN UP MATERIAL. THE DRUM WILL BE DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH EPA DISPOSAL REGULATIONS.
column169: THE HANDLING COMPANY AND LCAG WERE BRIEFED TO NOT MOVE A SLAVE DOLLY WITH DGR on THE ULD by only pushing on the forklift hole opening.  INSTEAD THE FORKLIFT BLADES MUST BE INSERTED INTO THE SLAVE DOLLY HOLES AND THEN THE SLAVE DOLLY CAN BE MOVED.

column168: THE BXI, LLC UNIT WAS LOADED WITH CRUDE COAL TAR OIL AND SPOTTED AT A SECURE LOCATION IN BRYAN, OHIO. AT SOME POINT WHILE THE TRAILER WAS STATIONARY, IT BEGAN TO LEAK. THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK APPEARS TO BE AN INTERNAL BRACKET THAT CORRODED AND BROKE LOOSE. THE BRACKET THEN RUBBED A HOLE IN THE TANK'S VENT LINE. THIS ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY 3000 GALLONS OF CRUDE COAL TAR OIL TO BE RELEASED. SUNPRO ENVIRONMENTAL IS HANDLING THE REMEDIATION.
column169: BXI, LLC WILL MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO THE TRAILER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE.

column168: At 1020 on 09/14/2016 ERTS was contacted by Jacques Atkins from XPO's NAT terminal. It was reported that material was found in the hazmat bay at the terminal but had not been reported. On 08/30/2016 @ 0400 A cardboard box containing four 1 gallon plastic containers of NA1760 Cleaning Compound was punctured by a forklift. The impact released approximately .5 gallons of material to the trailer floor.  The release was cleaned using granular absorbents. The used granular and the released material were placed into a 5 gallon poly pail, the other three containers were heavily impacted and placed into a separate poly pail as waste.  and placed into the hazmat bay with the appropriate labels.  Spills in trailers, concrete docks, containment areas, inside buildings are not into environment and not considered reportable,DOT 5800 is the only regulatory reporting required at this time.  There were no drains, soils, or waterways impacted by this incident. Titan Entry NAT-013208. Chemtel Notification 20163281

column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT HAZMAT'S DRIVERS 2ND PICKUP STOP ON A MULTI-STOP VAN RUN, HE NOTICE MATERIAL LEAKING OUT THE BACK OF TRAILER ONTO CUSTOMER'S PAVEMENT. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A PLASTIC DRUM FROM THE FREEST PICK UP LOCATION HAD HOLES IN IT TOWARDS THE BOTTOM, RELEASING APPROX. 2 GALS. SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITH SPEEDY DRY AND ABSORBENTS, AND TRAILER FLOOR WAS FIRED AS WELL BY THESE SAME METHODS. EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM, SET ENVIRONMENTAL, WAS CALLED IN BY THE CUSTOMER TO REMEDIATE THE SPILL. THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM THAT WAS STORED UNDERNEATH HAZMAT'S TRAILER TO BE TAKEN TO THE TSDF. THE TWO DRUMS OF DEBRIS THAT WERE GENERATED FROM THE CLEANUP WERE HANDLED ON SITE. THE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED AT THE BOTTOM LIP WITH TWO IDENTICAL ADJACENT HOLES. THIS WAS APPARENTLY CAUSED BY THE DRUM CART WHEN SITE EMPLOYEE WAS MOVING THE DRUM TO SCALE IT AND THE MOVING IT AGAIN TO STAGE IT TO BE LIFTED ONTO OUR TRAILER BY A DRUM PICKER.
column169: HAZMAT'S CUSTOMER WILL REVIEW LOADING METHODS WITH THE SHIPPER, TT ELECTRONICS TO DISCUSS REDUCING THE AMOUNT OF TIMES DRUMS ARE HANDLED PRIOR TO BEING LOADED ON OUR TRAILER. HAZMAT'S CUSTOMER SERVICE REP. WILL PLACE A NOTE ON THE DISPATCH ORDER FOR DRIVERS TO INSPECT DRUMS FOR POSSIBLE PUNCTURES PRIOR TO DEPARTING THIS GENERATOR SITE.

column168: On August 29, XPO terminal personnel accidentally punctured (4) 1-gallon poly jugs of UN1090 Acetone "S-W Duplicolor" during a forklift accident. Approximately 4-gallons released to the trailer floor of trailer #6638172. The terminal personnel utilized absorbents to contain and clean the release which were thoroughly worked into all impacted areas. The impacted absorbents were swept up and containerized into a (1) 85-gallon steel drum which was staged in OS&D for XPO to manage. XPO did not notify ERTS of the release until 11/9/16.

column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS HEADED NORTH ON COMMERCE ROAD INTENDING TO TURN RIGHT ONTO THE ENTRANCE RAMP TO I-95. THE VEHICLE WAS APPARENTLY GOING FASTER THAN IT SHOULD HAVE BEEN AND THE LOAD SHIFTED AS IT BEGAN TO TURN. THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO NEGOTIATE THE TURN AND THE TRUCK TURNED OVER ON ITS LEFT SIDE ROLLING OVER ONTO THE TOP. THE TANK STRUCK A JERSEY WALL THAT SEPARATES THE ON AND OFF SIDES OF THE RAMP CAUSING THE DOME LID ON THE FRONT COMPARTMENT TO POP OPEN, EMPTYING THE COMPARTMENT AND A HOLE TO OPEN IN THE REAR, DUE TO IMPACT, WHICH DRAINED THE PRODUCT FROM THE REMAINING COMPARTMENTS. THE PRODUCT WAS LOST OVER A PERIOD OF ROUGHLY AN HOUR. THE RICHMOND FIRE DEPT. WAS ON THE SCENE MANAGING THE SAFETY AND FIRE HAZARD ISSUES AND HEPACO, AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR WAS ON SITE VERY QUICKLY VACUUMING UP PRODUCT AS IT WAS DISCHARGED FROM THE TRUCK.     PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED FROM THE TRUCK, THE ROADWAY, STORM SEWERS, AND THE JAMES RIVER. ADDITIONAL PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED THROUGH SOIL REMOVAL AND REMEDIATION. WE BELIEVE WE RECOVERED ALL BUT 330 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.     VA-DEQ, US EPA, US COAST GUARD, VA DEPT. OF HIGHWAYS AND VA GAME AND INLAND FISHERIES ALL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AT VARIOUS TIMES. MORE DETAILED REPORTS COVERING THE CLEANUP AND REMEDIATION EFFORTS FOLLOWING THIS INCIDENT HAVE BEEN FILED WITH BOTH VA-DEQ AND EPA. IF THERE IS INTEREST, THEY CAN BE FORWARDED TO YOUR OFFICE AS WELL.
column169: WOODFIN HAS HAD A VEHICLE SAFETY PROGRAM IN PLACE FOR MANY YEARS NOW AND WE HAVE ALWAYS TAKEN SAFETY VERY SERIOUSLY. OUR CURRENT PROGRAM CONSISTS OF TRAINING REGULAR SAFETY MEETINGS, SAFETY AWARDS AND OTHER INCENTIVE PROGRAMS DESIGNED TO REDUCE THE LIKELIHOOD OF VEHICLE ACCIDENTS. WE WILL CONTINUE THOSE EFFORTS IN THE FUTURE. IN ADDITION, DUE IN PART TO THE SEVERITY OF THIS INCIDENT, WE HAD A SPECIAL SAFETY MEETING FOLLOWING THIS ACCIDENT FOR THE PURPOSE OF REFOCUSING OUR DRIVERS ON THE IMPORTANCE OF ATTENTIVE AND SAFE DRIVING. WE ARE ALWAYS LOOKING FOR NEW AND BETTER WAYS TO INSTILL THE VALUE OF SAFE DRIVING IN ALL OF OUR EMPLOYEES WHO OPERATE OUR VEHICLES, PARTICULARLY OUR LARGER TRUCKS.     THE DRIVER OF THIS PARTICULAR VEHICLE WAS ONE OF OUR MOST EXPERIENCED DRIVERS AND HAD BEEN THROUGH A THOROUGH TRAINING PROCESS TO ASSUMING HIS DUTIES AS A TRANSPORT DRIVER. HIS DRIVING RECORD WAS EXCELLENT AND HIS JOB PERFORMANCE PRIOR TO THE INCIDENT HAD BEEN VERY SATISFACTORY. FOLLOWING THE ACCIDENT, WE REASSIGNED HIM TO ANOTHER POSITION IN THE COMPANY WHERE HE IS NO LONGER DRIVING LARGE VEHICLES.     WE ARE IN THE PROCESS OF INSTALLING DRIVER-CAMS IN ALL OF OUR COMPANY VEHICLES AND ARE NEARLY DONE WITH THAT PROJECT. UNFORTUNATELY, IN THIS CASE, THE TRUCK WAS A RENTAL UNIT AND HAD NOT BEEN EQUIPPED WITH A CAMERA.

column43: SPENT PICKLE LIQUOR OUT FOR RECLAMATION
column168: ON AUGUST 29, 2016 AT 9:03AM. THOMAS STEEL STRIP CORPORATION (TSSC) HAD A RELEASE OF 880 POUNDS (LBS) OF FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION (REPORTABLE QUANITY [RQ] = 100 LBS) ONTO GRAVEL. THIS RELEASE WAS IMMEDIATELY REPORTED BY TELEPHONE TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (CASE # 1157580) AT 9:24AM. AND THE OHIO ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (OHIO EPA) (ID # 1608-78-1747) AT 9:29AM. ALTHOUGH AN RQ OF FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION DID NOT LEAVE TSSC’S PROPERTY BOUNDARY, THIS CORRESPONDENCE SERVES TSSC’S WRITTEN FOLLOW-UP NOTIFICATION OF THE REPORTABLE SPILL EVENT.     TSSC IS LOCATED ON DELAWARE AVENUE N.W., IN WARREN TOWNSHIP, TRUMBULL COUNTY. THOMAS PROCESSING COMPANY (TPC), PART OF TSSC, OPERATES A HYDROCHLORIC ACID PICKLING LINE FOR TSSC’S STEEL STRIP THAT IS PROCESSED FURTHER THROUGHOUT THE FACILITY. A BYPRODUCT OF THE PICKING PROCESS IS FERROUS CHLORIDE (CAS # 7758-94-3) SOLUTION. TYPICALLY, TPC USES ON-SITE REGENERATED FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION IN THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID PICKLING LINE SO THE FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION IS NOT TRANSPORTED OFFSITE. HOWEVER, THE ON-SITE FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION REGENERATION PLANT WAS DOWN FOR REPAIRS, AND ON AUGUST 29, 2016 THE FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION WAS BEING SHIPPED VIA TANKER TRUCK FOR RECLAMATION TO AMROX IN ALLENPORT, PENNSLYVANIA (SEE THE ENCLOSED BILL OF LADING).     THE RELEASE OF FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION OCCURRED DURING LOADING WHEN THE TANKER TRUCK OVERFLOWED. UPON DISCOVERY OF THE OVERFLOW, THE TSSC OPERATOR QUICKLY RESPONDED BY SHUTTING THE LOADING PUMP OFF. ONE WEEK PRIOR TO THIS INCIDENT, THE LOADING PUMP WAS REPLACED WITH A NEW HIGH VOLUME (150 GALLON PER MINUTE) ELECTRIC PUMP TO SPEED UP THE TANKER TRUCK LOADING PROCESS.     THE RELEASED MATERIAL OVERFLOWED THE CONTAINMENT TRENCH INSIDE THE LOADING BAY AND FLOWED ACROSS THE CEMENT ROADWAY ONTO THE GRAVEL ACROSS THE ROAD. THE WEATHER WAS CLEAR AND SUNNY AT THE TIME OF THE RELEASE, AND FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION DID NOT ENTER ANY STORM DRAINS. AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE, A HEAVY RUBBER SPILL PAD STORED NEAR THE LOADING AREA WAS PLACED ON TOP OF A STORM DRAIN LOCATED SIXTY FEET FROM THE SPILL AREA. THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS THEN NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE OVER AN AREA OF APPROXIMATELY 40 SQUARE FEET. THE AREA IMPACTED BY THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS MONITORED WITH PH PAPER. THE DISCHARGED TO THE OHIO EPA PERMIT NO. 3IC00456*KD, OUTFALL 3IC00056001 WAS ALSO MONITORED, AND A SAMPLE WAS COLLECTED AND ANALYZED (SEE ENCLOSED LABORATORY ANALYSIS). NO PERMIT DISCHARGE VIOLATIONS OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF THIS FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION RELEASE. THE FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION RELEASE DID NOT RESULT IN DAMAGE TO ANY WILDLIFE TO ANY WILDLIFE OR VEGETATION OR A THREAT TO HUMAN HEALTH AND SAFETY. THE AMOUNT OF FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION RELEASED WAS VALUED AT $10, AND THE COST OF THE SODIUM BICARBONATE USED NEUTRALIZE THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS VALUED AT $1,765.     CHEMTRON CORPORATION WAS HIRED TO REMEDIATE THE IMPACTED AREA AND TO TRANSPORT AND DISPOSE OF THE 28 TO 30

column14: Lease road off of N Waldo Road
column168: While cargo tank was loading, the driver started putting equipment in the tool box when the overfill alarm sounded. He ran to the opposite side of the cargo tank to shut off the pump and close the load valve. Once the product filled the cargo tank it entered the vent pipe and vented out onto the ground and spread out covering an area about 30ft. x 5 ft. Approximately 5 gallons got into a ditch. The driver built a dirt berm to prevent further spreading. Company personnel responded, called a clean up crew and Michigan DEQ. Puddled spillage was vacuumed up. Impacted soil was excavated clean in accordance with Michigan DEQ requirements and removed from the site for disposal. New soil and rock were put in.
column169: Responsible driver completed remedial training on loading/unloading procedures and spill prevention control and countermeasures. The cause of the spill, distraction-inattention was reviewed with all personnel in safety meetings.

column168: The package was unloaded with leakage noted on the box.  Examination of the inner container revealed that the container(s) had loose cap(s) and leaked.  The leakage was contained.  The cap(s) were secured.  The carton was wet but otherwise undamaged.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.

THE WHEN LOADING, THE BULK CAUSTIC SODA LOADER FAILED TO CHECK DISCHARGE VALVE WHICH WAS OPEN. WHEN THE RELEASE WAS DISCOVERED THE LOADER SHUT THE VALVE BUT THERE WAS AN ESTIMATED LOSS OF 25 GALLONS. PERSONNEL BEGAN CUTTING IN THE PIT AREA AND COVERED THE STORM SEWER. THE CITY OF LACROSSE WAS NOTIFIED. THEIR REPRESENTATIVES FOUND A GALLON OF CAUSTIC AT THE BOTTOM OF THE SEWER. THE CITY AND THE DNR AGREED THAT AN ABSORBENT PAD BE USED TO SOAK UP THE SMALL AMOUNT OF CAUSTIC INT HE SEWER.
column169: WE HAVE STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES IN PLACE TO PREVENT INCIDENTS LIKE THIS. HYDRITE PERSONNEL DID NOT FOLLOW OUR WRITTEN PROCEDURES AND WILL BE RETRAINED ON ALL THE PROCEDURES RELATIVE TO BULK LOADING.

column168: SHAWN CLIMBED A HILL IN PENDLETON THAT HE SHOULD NOT HAVE CLIMBED. A TOTE CAME LOOSE FROM ITS STRAP IN FRONT OF THE MAIN TANK + CRUSHED THE MAIN VALVE ON THE TANK. THE TANK WAS THEN EVACUATED INTO AN EMPTY LOT. THERE WAS NO STOPPING THE EVACUATION AT THAT POINT. THE AREA WAS EXCAVATED TO THE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITIES SPECIFICATION.
column169: WE HAVE REVIEWED OUR PROCEDURES FOR LOAD SECUREMENT.  OUR EMPLOYEES HAVE BEEN TRAINED TO BE TO ENSURE THEIR LOAD IS SECURE BEFORE TRANSPORT.

column168: DRIVER WAS LOADING COMPARTMENTS 2 (1000 GAL) AND COMPARTMENT 3 (2000 GAL) FOR DELIVERY TO CUSTOMERS. DURING THE LOADING PROCESS HE ATTACHED THE LOADING HEAD WITH A PRESET METER FOR 2000 GALLONS TO COMPARTMENT 2 AND A LOADING HEAD WITH A PRESET METER FOR 1000 GALLONS TO COMPARTMENT 3. COMPARTMENT 2 REACHED CAPACITY AND OVERFILLED EXCESS PRODUCT WAS DISCHARGED THROUGH VAPOR RECOVERY VENT. -THE DRIVER INITIATED SHUT DOWN PROCEDURES IMMEDIATELY. TOTAL DURATION OF RELEASE LESS THAN 12 SECONDS AND APPROXIMATELY 59 GALLONS WERE RELEASED. FLOW OF THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED USING OIL DRI AND PETROLEUM ABSORBENT BOOMS, A SMALL AMOUNT FLOWED INTO THE FACILITY WATER QUALITY VAULT. FIRST RESPONSE (ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION COMPANY) WAS CONTACTED AND THEY PUMPED OUT THE CONTAMINATED WATER/DIESEL FUEL MIXTURE AND DISPOSED OF THE DRY MEDIA ABSORBENTS.

column168: ON AUGUST 9, 2016, AT APPROXIMATELY 22:05 A BARGE UNLOADING 1 METHOXY 2 PROPANOL SHIFTED FROM IT MOORINGS AND SEVERED THE UNLOADING HOSE.     WITHIN SECONDS, PERSONNEL IN THE AREA IMMEDIATELY STOPPED FLOW, HOWEVER, 220 GALLONS WAS RELEASED. 30 GALLONS IS ESTIMATED TO HAVE SPILLED INTO CARPENTERS BAYOU, THE REMAINING MATERIAL ON THE BARGE AND BARGE DOCK.    NO ONE WAS INJURED.     1 METHOXY 2 PROPANOL IS TOTALLY SOLUBLE IN WATER. SO THERE WAS NO EFFORT TO CLEAN UP THE MATERIAL SPILLED IN THE BAYOU.     AT 22:10 EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL ARRIVE AND DEPLOYED SPILL PADS. A FIRE MONITOR IS USED TO SPRAY THE BARGE DOCK TO REDUCE VAPORS. MATERIAL IS ROUTED INTO A SUMP SYSTEM AND PUMPED TO WASTE STORAGE TANKS.     A VACUUM TRUCK WAS USED TO SUCK OUT MATERIAL FROM THE HOSE AND TO CLEAN OFF THE BARGE. ALL CLEANUP ACTIVITIES WERE COMPLETED BY 2:40 AM ON 8/10/2016.
column169: UPDATED THE BARGE OFF-LOADING PROCEDURE TO INCLUDE VERY SPECIFIC LANGUAGE ABOUT HOW A BARGE IS TIED OFF BEFORE OFFLOADING.     SHARED INCIDENT INVESTIGATION FINDINGS WITH KIRBY INLAND MARINE.

column168: THE KAG WEST, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO LOAD RENEWABLE DIESEL FUEL INTO THE TANK TRAILER AT THE SHIPPER'S LOADING FACILITY IN KINGMAN, ARIZONA. AFTER LOADING AN ESTIMATE 100-200 GALLONS OF RENEWABLE DIESEL FUEL THERE WAS A SUDDEN EXPLOSION NEAR THE SHIPPER'S LOADING LINES. THE INITIAL THEORY AS TO THE CAUSE OF THE EXPLOSION IS A BUILD-UP OF STATIC ELECTRICITY IN THE SHIPPER'S LOADING LINES. AS A RESULT OF THE EXPLOSION AND FIRE, THE KAG WEST, LLC TRACTOR AND TANK TRAILER WERE COMPLETELY CONSUMED ALONG WITH THE SHIPPER'S LOADING FACILITIES. THE SHIPPER WAS UNABLE TO IMMEDIATELY STOP THE FLOW OF RENEWABLE DIESEL FUEL FROM THE LOADING LINES AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ESTIMATES THAT A TOTAL OF 20,000 GALLONS WAS RELEASED/CONSUMED BY FIRE. THE SHIPPER CONTACTED H20 ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE AND HANDLE THE REMEDIATION.

column168: OAKLEY TRANSPORT DRIVER WAS ON MCCRACKEN PIKE ROAD, JUST LEAVING THE SHIPPER – WOODFORD RESERVE. THE OAKLEY DRIVER (DAVID NARDONE) STATED THAT ANOTHER WAS TRAVELING TOWARDS HIM AND WAS PARTIALLY ON HIS LANE.     MR. NARDONE MOVED TO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD WHICH CAUSED HIS RIGHT STEER TIRE AND RIGHT DRIVE TIRES TO GET EMBEDDED IN THE SOFT SOIL OF THE SHOULDER- CAUSING THE UNIT SHIFT TO THE RIGHT.     THE MOMENTUM CAUSED THE TRUCK AND THE TRAILER TO ROLL OVER 1+ TIMES, COMING TO REST ON THE LEFT SIDE. THE TRUCK AND TRAILER ROLLED OVER A WOODEN FENCE BELONGING TO WOODFORD RESERVE AND A PIECE OF THE WOOD COMPROMISED THE DOME, SLIGHTLY. DUE TO THE LEVEL OF THE LIQUID INSIDE THE TANK, THE PRODUCT VAPOR LOCKED WHICH PREVENTED THE PRODUCT FROM FLOWING FREELY.     THE OAKLEY SAFETY DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED IMMEDIATELY AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE SWS (OUR CONTRACTED VENDOR FOR SPILLS) CONTACT A LOCAL COMPANY (PERDUE) TO GO TO THE SCENE TO CONTROL THE SITE. I HAVE INCLUDED THE ERS OF PERDUE WITH THE WASTE MANIFESTS WHICH INCLUDE THE CLEAN-UP OF SOME DIESEL FUEL THAT LEAKED OUT WHILE THE TRUCK WAS ON ITS SIDE.

column63: UN1267, PETROLEUM CRUDE OIL, 3, PG II
column168: ANTHONY CLAY. A TURNER GUS CRUDE DRIVER IN ITS RAWLINS DIVISION, SPILLED APPROXIMATELY  115 BARRELS OF CRUDE OIL WHILE HE WAS DRIVING BUCK FROM SAND RIDGE (NORTHPARK, COLORADO) EN ROUTE TO SINCLAIR'S RAWLINS/GETTY LACT 011 THE LATE EVENING OF AUGUST 10, 2016. THE SPILL WAS THE RESULT OF A ROLLOVER AND SUBSEQUENT BREAK IN THE REAR COMPARTMENT OF THE TANKER TRAILER. THE SPILL OCCURRED ON HIGHWAY 125 AT MILE MARKER 68 OFF THE SIDE OF THE ROAD. NO CRUDE SPILLED INTO ANY WATER SOURCE AND  WAS QUICKLY CONTAINED,    BACKGROUND AND PRIOR TRAINING: TURNER HAS CONDUCTED SPECIFIC TRAINING FOR DRIVERS PRIOR TO THEM GOING OUT IN THE FIELD, AND CAN CONFIRM IT CONDUCTED TRAINING WITH MR. CLAY, INCLUDING DRIVING TESTS, REQUIRED SAFETY VIDEOS, RIDE A LONGS WITH OUR CERTIFIED TRAINER, AND STANDARD DIVER SAFETY INSTRUCTIONS. MR. CLAY HAS BEEN WITH TURNER FOR APPROXIMATELY 3 MONTHS AND CAME TO TURNER WITH OVER 5 YEARS OF CRUDE EXPERIENCE, AND APPROXIMATELY 20 YEARS DRIVING EXPERIENCE OVERALL. HE HAS NO MAJOR ACCIDENTS, SPEEDING OR OTHER PRIOR CITATIONS ON HIS MVR THE LAST 5+ YEARS DRIVING. FURTHERMORE, HE HAD BEEN HAULING CRUDE OIL ON THE SAND RIDGE ROUTE SINCE SHORTLY AFTER JUNE 1 (OVER 60 DAYS), AND HAS BEEN ON THIS ROUTE MULTIPLE TIME PRIOR TO THE INCIDENT WITHOUT ANY PRIOR ISSUES.    TUNER GAS HAS CONDUCTED OUR PRELIMINARY INTERNAL INVESTIGATION, RECEIVED THE DRIVER DRUG/ALCOHOL RESULTS AND THE HIGHWAY PATROL VERBAL REPORT.     1 DRIVER REPORT: MR. CLAY INDICATED THAT IT WAS RAINING OUT AND HE WAS GOING APPROXIMATELY 45 MPH.  HE HAD CRESTED OVER A HILL ON THE ROAD HEADING NORTH ON HIGHWAY 125, THE ROAD LEVELED OFF, AND BELIEVES HE HEARD A "POP" IN THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE TRUCK WHICH CAUSED THE TRUCK TO PULL TO THE RIGHT.  THERE IS A LIMITED SHOULDER ON THIS ROAD TO PULL OVER/CORRECT AND NEXT THING HE KNEW HE WAS IN THE DITCH ROLLED OVER.    2 HIGHWAY PATROL REPORT: TURNER HAS REQUESTED THE FORMAL WRITTEN COLORADO HIGHWAY PATROL REPORT ON 8/ 15, AND THEY SAID IT MAY TAKE UP TO 10 DAYS. WE WILL FORWARD AS SOON AS WE RECEIVE. THE HIGHWAY PATROL DID NOT ISSUE A CITATION TO THE DRIVER AT THE SCENE. IN A VERBAL CONVERSATION WITH MARK MERRITT ON 8/1 5, THE REPORTING OFFICER STATED THAT HE WILL NOT BE ISSUING A CITATION TO THE DRIVER OR TO TURNER FOR ANY EQUIPMENT RELATED ISSUES. THE OFFICER SAID HE DID NOT FIND ANY SPECIFIC EQUIPMENT RELATED ISSUES THAT MAY HAVE CAUSED THIS INCIDENT, BUT ALSO DOES NOT HAVE ANY SUPPORTING EVIDENCE TO LEAD TO THE DRIVER BEING AT FAULT. THE HIGHWAY PATROL ESTIMATED THE DRIVER SPEED LIT BETWEEN 40 AND 45 MPH.    3: TURNER REPORT : THE DRUG/ALCOHOL SCREEN BOTH CAME BACK NEGATIVE (SEE SUPPORTING DOCUMENTATION), WE HAVE INSPECTED THE EQUIPMENT AS WELL AND CAN FIND NOTHING THAT CAUSED THE ''POP" THAT THE DRIVER REPORTED THAT WOULD HAVE DIRECTLY CAUSED THIS I INCIDENT. OUR GPS REPORT ON SPEED ALSO CAME BACK UNDER 45 MPH. WE DO NOTE THAT THERE IS LIMITED CELL RECEPTION ON THIS ROUTE SO WE DON'T BELIEVE THAT TO BE A FACTOR. THIS WAS ALSO THE FI
column169: ACTION ITEMS TURNER IS TAKING TO PREVENT THIS FROM OCCURRING AGAIN IN THE FUTURE:    1)TURNER HAS CONDUCTED SAFETY TRAINING SINCE THE INCIDENT, AND WILL CONDUCT ADDITIONAL TRAINING SESSIONS OVER THE COMING WEEKS TO REINFORCE PROPER TRAINING/SAFETY PROTOCOLS AND THE IMPORTANCE OF EXERCISING MORE CAUTION. DISTRACTIONS ARE PRESENT WITH DRIVING ESPECIALLY ON MOUNTAIN TERMINI. WE ARE THEREFORE CONDUCTING FURTHER SPECIFIC TRAINING FOR THE SAND RIDGE HAUL. THESE TRAINING SESSIONS WILL BE CONDUCTED IN PERSON IN SMALL 3 PERSON CLASS SETTINGS, AND WILL ALSO INCLUDE ONLINE TRAINING VIDEOS ON DEFENSIVE TANKER DRIVING, SAFE DRIVING, AND A FOCUS ON ANTI-DISTRACTION PROTOCOLS.    2)WE WILL CONDUCT MORE FREQUENT AUDITS TO ENSURE PROTOCOLS ARE BEING MET TO THE STANDARDS TURNER AND SINCLAIR/PRODUCERS REQUIRE.    TURNER GAS COMPANY TAKES THIS INCIDENT VERY SERIOUSLY AND WILL CONTINUE TO ENFORCE SAFETY TO PREVENT THIS FROM OCCURRING AGAIN IN THE FUTURE.

column168: THE TERMINAL INSTALLED A FIELD-ASSEMBLED COUPLING TO THE CTMV UNLOADING LINE. OUR DRIVER CONNECTED THE HOSE AT THE CONSIGNEE LOCATION TO THE COUPLING AND BEGAN UNLOADING THE CTMV.
